	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64624801"><p><div class="quote"><p>100+ years ago, a 7-day work week was common. "Good" businesses gave people one day off per week. Then Henry Ford came along and popularized the five-day work week, as a way to encourage people to take road trips in the cars he sold them. <a href="https://firmspace.com/theproworker/from-strikes-to-labor-laws-how-the-us-adopted-the-5-day-workweek" title="firmspace.com">https://firmspace.com/theprowo...</a> [firmspace.com] Everybody thought it was fantastic...until a five day work week became normal.</p><p>The same will happen to a 4-day work week. People will think it's great, until it becomes normal, and then the same old grumpiness will set in.</p></div><p>That would be the logical conclusion.  If four days is good, three would be better, and so on.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64624801">

</div>
</div>

